You should not have complained by phone, you should have complained in
writing. Didn't you notice where it's written on your statement that
complaining by phone doesn't preserve your rights? By now it's
probably too long since the charge you're disputing first showed up on
your statement for Chase to be legally required to allow you to dispute
it -- they are only required to accept a dispute if you make it in
writing within 60 days of when you receive the statement with the
charge on it.

Nevertheless, you should immediately locate on your statement the
address to which you're supposed to send complaints, and send a
*written* complaint to Chase, disputing the charge and telling them the
same story you just posted, with all the details you can provide (i.e.,
the date on which you canceled the card by phone, the dates on which
you spoke to people about the unauthorized Privacy Guard charges, the
people to whom you spoke, etc.). It is likely that Chase will remove
the charge, interest and fees from your balance in response to this
letter.

If they don't, come back here and let us know and I'm sure people will
have suggestions for what to try next.

