&quot;Send a certified letter, return receipt requested, to the disputes
address (not the payment address; the dispute address should be on your

bill). &quot;

There is no need to panic and DO NOT pay those bogus charges.

Simply regroup by writing as instructed above and open your letter with
the the fact that you did call their customer service deparment on &quot;x&quot;
date and spoke to &quot;x&quot; (hopefully, you wrote down at least the date you
called.. the name of the rep is a bonus). Then explain what you were
told your account would be credited in full but that hasn't happened,
so you have been forced to write.

Explain when you wrote and asked that your account be closed, be firm
in the fact that you never authorized Privacy Guard to make any
charges to your account and repeat that you were told by both Chase and
Privacy Guard that these charges would be credited.

Close by explaining that you want the promised credit applied
immediately, including a credit for finance and late fees on those
charges. In the end, your account should have a zero balance as it did
before the unauthorized charges and ask for a letter to confirm.

I had a similar problem with Chase. They can't seem to understand that
when someone says CLOSE THIS ACCOUNT, they want it CLOSED, not sitting
there dormant!

The letter with note that you did call should clear the situation up.
Keep a copy of everything and your next statement should show all the
credits assuming it's not in the mail before your letter reaches them.

In the future, it's probably best to write first however. That way you
have a record that they were notified in writing and that it was
received.

</POST>



